Data

  • Stat2Data package: info here
    • MedGPA dataset (\(n\) = 55)
      • Acceptance: accepted in medical school (0 = no, 1 = yes)
      • Sex: F=female or M=male
      • BCPM: Bio/Chem/Physics/Math grade point average
      • GPA: College grade point average
      • VR: Verbal reasoning (subscore)
      • PS: Physical sciences (subscore)
      • WS: Writing sample (subcore)
      • BS: Biological sciences (subscore)
      • MCAT: Score on the MCAT exam (sum of VR+PS+WS+BS)
      • Apps: Number of medical schools applied to
  • When you use a dataset thatâs in a package, you donât read it in the same way
    • Load the package: library(Stat2Data)
    • Load the dataset: data(MedGPA)
    • The data is in a dataframe with the same name: MedGPA
library(Stat2Data)

Models

GPA predicts Acceptance

Scatterplot of Acceptance (Y) vs GPA (X)

  • The options in geom_smooth() tell it to fit a logistic regression curve
    • method = "glm" : use a generalized linear model
    • method.args = list(family = "binomial") : specifically, use a logistic regression (i.e., binomial outcome)
ggplot(data = MedGPA, aes(x = GPA, y = Acceptance)) + 
    geom_point(alpha = 0.2, size = 5) +
    geom_smooth(method = "glm", 
                method.args = list(family = "binomial"), 
                se = TRUE)
`geom_smooth()` using formula = 'y ~ x'

Logistic regression model

  • GPA is centered at its mean (3.553)
  • glm() works very much like lm()
    • Additional options specify the type of GLiM
      • Here, logistic regression (with binomial outcome distribution and logit link function) is specified by family = binomial(link = "logit")
MedGPA <- MedGPA %>% mutate(GPAc = GPA - mean(GPA))
Acc_GPA <- glm(Acceptance ~ GPAc, MedGPA, family = binomial(link = "logit"))

summary() of the model

  • The statements involving NULL are just dropping the column labels from those variables
    • Otherwise the labels will follow them around whenever we use the variables

Interpretation

Intercept

  • Probability of acceptance when GPAc = 0

    • \(P(success|X = 0) = \frac{e^{b_0}}{1 + e^{b_0}}\) =
prob_X0 <- exp(GPA_b0) / (1 + exp(GPA_b0))
prob_X0
[1] 0.5433003
  • A person with GPAc = 0 (mean GPA) has 0.54 probability of being accepted to med school
    • Greater than 0.5, so more likely to be accepted than not
  • You can also convert this to odds:
odds_X0 <- prob_X0 / (1 - prob_X0)
odds_X0
[1] 1.189623
  • A person with GPAc = 0 (mean GPA) has 1.19 odds of being accepted to med school
    • Greater than 1, so more likely to be accepted than not
  • And letâs go wild and convert it to logit too:
logit_X0 <- log(odds_X0)
logit_X0
[1] 0.1736361
  • A person with GPAc = 0 (mean GPA) has 0.174 logit of being accepted to med school
    • Positive, so more likely to be accepted than not

Slope

  • From the slope, you can calculate the odds ratio
odds_ratio <- exp(GPA_b1) 
odds_ratio
[1] 233.7298
  • The odds ratio is the multiplicative change in the odds for a 1 unit change in the predictor
    • Constant multiplicative change
    • For every 1 unit increase in GPAc, we expect the predicted odds to get multiplied by 233.73
  • For probability metric, use the predicted values instead (below)
  • For logit metric, itâs just a linear effect

Predicted values

  • This is just one way to do this that I find the easiest
    • Grab the \(b_0\) and \(b_1\) values from the output
      • We already saved these above as variables: GPA_b0 and GPA_b1
    • Create some X values that correspond to the predictor
      • Centered GPA ranges from about \(-1\) to about \(+0.5\)
      • Donât include too many values or the table will get too large
    • Calculate the predicted probability using the equations from lecture
      • Calculate the slope for the probability line using that
    • Use that to calculate predicted odds and predicted logit
    • Combine all the variables into a data frame
x <- c(-1, -0.75, -0.5, -0.25, 0, 0.25, 0.5)
pred_prob <- exp(GPA_b0 + GPA_b1 * x) / (1 + exp(GPA_b0 + GPA_b1 * x))
pred_prob_slope <- pred_prob*(1 - pred_prob)*GPA_b1
pred_odds <- pred_prob / (1 - pred_prob)
pred_logit <- log(pred_odds)
predicted <- data.frame(x, pred_prob, pred_prob_slope, pred_odds, pred_logit)
predicted

    geom_point(alpha = 0.2, size = 5) +
    geom_smooth(method = "glm", 
                method.args = list(family = "binomial"), 
                se = TRUE)
`geom_smooth()` using formula = 'y ~ x'

  • This doesnât look much like the S-shaped curve we saw before, does it?
    • Thatâs because itâs a very flat curve and we only see a tiny part of it
    • Letâs zoom out using
      • xlim(-100, 100) in ggplot() to expand the X axis from -100 to 100
      • fullrange = TRUE option in the geom_smooth() to extend the line
ggplot(data = MedGPA, aes(x = Apps, y = Acceptance)) + 
    geom_point(alpha = 0.2, size = 5) +
    geom_smooth(method = "glm", 
                method.args = list(family = "binomial"), 
                se = FALSE,
                fullrange = TRUE) +
    xlim(-100, 100)
`geom_smooth()` using formula = 'y ~ x'

  • Two things:
    • See? It really is an S-shaped curve, itâs just backward
    • This backwards S corresponds to a negative slope
    • So letâs look at the model
